## UI (`@neurex/ui` + consumer-installed stack)

Reference components in `packages/ui`. Consumers receive **copies** from `packages/registry/templates`, not a runtime `@neurex/ui` dependency.

### Direct dependencies (`packages/ui/package.json`)

| Dependency | Purpose |
|------------|---------|
| `@neurex/tokens` | Token CSS variables and design contract |
| `@base-ui/react` | Accessible headless behavior — **stable 1.x API** |
| `class-variance-authority` | `cva()` variant maps in `*.variants.ts` |
| `clsx` | Class list composition |
| `tailwind-merge` | `cn()` utility (with `clsx`) |
| `lucide-react` | Icons in reference components |

### Peer dependencies

- `react`, `react-dom` — `>=19` (peer requirement bumped from 18 in lockstep with Base UI stable)

### Registry → consumer dependencies (typical)

Most interactive components declare:

```txt
@base-ui/react
class-variance-authority
clsx
tailwind-merge
```

**Also `lucide-react`** on: Accordion (collapsible chevrons), AlertDialog, Collapsible, Dialog, Drawer, Menu, Popover, Select, Toast.

**No `@base-ui/react`** on presentational-only items such as **Alert** and **Badge** (CVA + clsx + tailwind-merge only).

### Styling stack

- **Tailwind CSS v4** — user-facing utility classes in `*.variants.ts`
- **Generated CSS variables** — `--nx-*` from `@neurex/tokens` / installed `tokens.css` + `theme.css`
- **Semantic classes** — `nx-` prefix where defined (see `docs/STYLE.md`)

### UI best practices

- Keep the file split: `Component.tsx`, `Component.types.ts`, `Component.variants.ts`
- Compose classes with shared `cn()` (installed as `src/lib/utils.ts` in consumers)
- Use `cva()` for variants; avoid long inline class strings in JSX
- Do not import `@neurex/ui` in consumer apps after CLI install — edit owned files under `paths.components` (default `src/components/ui/`)
- Preserve Base UI accessibility props and structure when wrapping primitives — the 1.x stable API is the contract
- Export public symbols in one block at the bottom of `Component.tsx`
- Current components use `forwardRef`; React 19 supports `ref` as a regular prop (no `forwardRef` needed) — do not refactor existing components but prefer the React 19 pattern for new ones
- `@base-ui/react` is now stable (1.x) — treat its API as stable; avoid reaching into internal subpaths

